In [[Indic scripts]], the '''danda''' ([[Sanskrit]]: दण्ड ''{{IAST|daṇḍa}}'' "stick") is a [[punctuation]] [[character (computing)|character]]. The [[glyph]] consists of a single vertical stroke. The character can be found at [[character encoding|code point]] U+0964 ({{script|Deva|&#x0964;}}) in [[Unicode]]. The "double danda" is at  U+0965 ({{script|Deva|&#x0965;}}). [[ISCII]] encodes danda at 0xEA.

The danda marks the end of a sentence or period, comparable to a [[full stop]] (period) as commonly used in the [[Latin alphabet]], and is used alternate with Western punctuation in most modern [[Languages of India|Indic]] languages. In metrical texts, a double danda is used to delimit verses, and a single danda to delimit a [[pada (foot)|pada]] or semi-verse.

